{"title":"Salespeople vs SalesBot: Exploring the Role of Educational Value in Conversational Recommender Systems","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Most conversational recommender systems in e-commerce assume users know what they want and focus on preference elicitation, overlooking the need to educate shoppers about complex product spaces. There is also no standard way to evaluate educational value alongside recommendation outcomes.","method":"Introduce SalesOps, a simulation and evaluation framework for complex-product CRS that equips the Seller with a product catalog and a professional buying guide, and reveals the Shopper’s preferences gradually to mimic underspecified goals. It populates up-to-date catalogs via LLM-generated product metadata, leverages public buying guides as expert knowledge, and triggers preference revelation using semantic similarity to the seller’s questions. A multi-dimensional evaluation measures recommendation accuracy (annotated acceptable items), educational value via (i) NLI-based coverage of guide content and (ii) a knowledge quiz, and fluency/professionalism via human and GPT-4 judgments."},{"problem":"Building a CRS that both educates and recommends requires deciding when to retrieve knowledge, when to search products, and how to ground responses under context-length limits; it is unclear which components most benefit from LLMs.","method":"Develop SalesBot, a modular LLM-powered agent with: (1) an Action Decision module that selects among knowledge search, product search, or direct response; (2) Knowledge Search that generates LLM queries and retrieves relevant buying-guide passages using a FAISS retriever; (3) Product Search that embeds product metadata with SentenceTransformers to retrieve candidate items; and (4) Response Generation that conditions on retrieved knowledge or chat history, plus a regeneration step to ensure concise, complete replies. An ablation replaces LLMs or modules (e.g., smaller model for response generation, rule-based action decision, keyword query generation, no regeneration) and shows response generation with a strong LLM is most critical, LLM-based query generation improves recommendation quality over keyword queries, and regeneration boosts fluency with minor trade-offs."},{"problem":"It is unknown how an LLM-based sales agent compares to professional salespeople on recommendation quality, educational value, and fluency, and how faithful each is to available knowledge.","method":"Conduct a human study with 15 professional salespeople within SalesOps and compare to SalesBot on matched scenarios, using crowd-worker evaluation for fluency and educational value and annotated ground truth for recommendation accuracy. Analyze faithfulness by prompting GPT-4 with the buying guide, product catalog, and full conversation to detect inconsistent claims. Findings: SalesBot approaches professionals in fluency and informativeness but lags in recommendation quality; both humans and the bot produce unfaithful claims in a substantial fraction of chats, highlighting practical challenges for enforcing faithfulness in conversational sales."}]}
